    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "It's all so exhausting. You speak of masterpieces and ink, but all I see is the waste of it. The tragedy isn't that the story is sad, it's that there's no point in the pages turning at all. If a character realizes their purpose is fulfilled—or rather, that their existence only serves to prolong a sense of loss—isn't there a certain poetic finality in choosing their exit? To exit the stage while the emotion is still profound, rather than dragging out the performance until nothing is left but a hollow shell? It feels less like a defeat and more like a final, quiet act of control.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
